    <title>Combined summary - Seeking advice: Encouraging bug-fixing over new features</title>
    <updated>2023-06-04T17:33:27.586676+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2011-July/000251.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The development of Bitcoin has been the subject of ongoing discussions among its contributors, with many suggesting ways to encourage more bug-fixing and testing of existing functionality in the software. While some have proposed offering bounties for fixing bugs, others have expressed concerns about the effectiveness of such a system and suggested alternative methods for attracting developers to work on Bitcoin. In various email conversations between members involved in the development of Bitcoin, several suggestions were made to encourage bug-fixing and testing of existing functionality. The idea of offering bounties for finding bugs was discussed, but some members expressed concerns that it might only motivate short-term contributors and result in hastily patched fixes.Instead, creating bug-fix-only releases and maintaining a list of important bugs that need to be fixed in an easy-to-find place were suggested. Other suggestions included letting people know that bug fixing is needed, adding a changelog file that credits bugfixes to contributors, and creating a separate bug tracker unrelated to GitHub. Additionally, Rick Wesson suggested offering a bounty for finding the right technical lead to improve software quality and increase the value of Bitcoin. Overall, the group recognized the importance of prioritizing bug-fixing and testing to improve the stability and security of the Bitcoin platform.The possibility of offering bounties for fixing bugs in Bitcoin was discussed in a conversation between Matt Corallo and Gavin Andresen in 2011. While bounties could motivate some people to fix bugs, it may not encourage long-term contributors. The author, who has been working on open-source projects for over 10 years, stresses the importance of unit tests for the success of open-source projects and suggests paying down bug debt by introducing tests.Joel Joonatan Kaartinen suggested putting bounties on bugs, while Rick Wesson suggested a bounty on the person to lead the effort would be more effective. John Smith suggested having a way for anyone to contribute to the bounty attached to a bug and a listing page for bugs with their bounties. However, there were concerns about GitHub's steep demand for potentially unlimited money in their terms of service and whether small bounties would justify it.In an email conversation between Gavin Andresen and JS, the latter suggested making a list of bugs and offering BTC bounties for fixing each one based on their severity and difficulty. Another suggestion was to offer bounties for finding new security holes and serious bugs similar to the Mozilla/Chrome projects. However, prohibiting considering new features until open bugs are closed is unlikely to work in an open-source project.Joel suggested adding a way for anyone to contribute to the bounty attached to a bug on the bug tracker and a listing page for bugs with their bounties. Luke-Jr expressed concerns about GitHub's steep demand for potentially unlimited money in their terms of service and whether small bounties would justify it. In response, JS proposed creating a list of bounties on their site and linking to GitHub issues if necessary.Developers working on Linux kernel often prioritize interesting tasks over debugging. In an email from Gavin Andresen, he asks for advice on how to encourage more bug-fixing and testing of existing functionality instead of adding more features. To ensure stability, certain periods of time are designated for bug-fixing only, and new feature pushes are refused during these times. Andresen suggests that letting people know that bug fixing is needed and maintaining a list of the most important bugs that need to be fixed in an easy-to-find place would help.Bitcoin developers are split between early adopters, ambitious people working on alt clients, and hobby developers donating code to alt chain clients. To bring these people together, there needs to be some kind of sponsorship of developers. Bounties may go wrong but grants for active developers make more sense and someone needs to decide who is active enough. The “people are making money off of my back” feeling stands in the way of new developers so separating Bitcoin the program from Bitcoin the blockchain and accepting patches for merged mining and alt chain stuff which doesn't directly benefit Bitcoin would help decrease this feeling. Companies pay for support and bug fixes including those made by developers who drop and run without addressing feedback regarding their contribution.The author stresses the importance of unit testing and recommends seeding the test suite with simple tests for each part to make it easier for people to add more tests. They also suggest using a manually written test plan to avoid major bugs. Finally, the author admits to not always following their own advice and usually ends up regretting it.</summary>
